player.seasonOutlook: Gallagher is the spark plug for Montreal, and he's set to continue filling that role for six more years after signing a lucrative extension. He was limited to 59 appearances last season by a variety of injuries after not missing a game over the previous two, but his 22 goals and 43 points had him on pace for a third straight year with 30 and 50. Gallagher still ranked 15th league-wide in shots despite the missed time with 226 after finishing sixth in the category in 2018-19, and his north-south style should continue to yield robust goal and shot totals. The 28-year-old winger's postseason was ended by a broken jaw, but Gallagher should be good to go for the start of 2020-21.

Werenski's 20 goals (in 63 games) led defensemen last season and were four more than Alex Pietrangelo rang up. Werenski is a well above-average offensive defenseman and an exciting fantasy commodity, but there's a real chance that his astronomical goal total was the result of a likely unsustainable 10.7 shooting percentage. For comparison's sake, his marks in the two prior seasons were 6.5 and 7.7. Werenski will help fantasy managers regardless, but those drafting him this season should plan for a few less lamp-lighters from the soon-to-be 24-year-old.

Koskinen's second season in Edmonton (2.75 GAA, .917 save percentage) was better than his first (2.93, .906) statistically, but he allowed four or more goals on eight separate occasions -- which resulted in the Oilers bringing back old friend Mike Smith on a one-year deal this offseason. Koskinen should have a slight leg up on Smith for the No. 1 job, but it's clear both goaltenders are going to play regularly. This has the look of a timeshare, and Koskinen probably isn't good enough to make up for any significant lack of playing time.

Severson's 31 points and minus-20 rating last season were right in line with his production from the previous three, in which he averaged 31.3 points and a minus-22 rating. The 26-year-old defenseman appears to have plateaued, and there's little reason to expect a significant step forward in 2021. An improvement in the team around him would provide more opportunities for offense and mitigate some of Severson's deficiencies in his own end, but that doesn't look to be in the cards for a Devils team that's expected to languish near the bottom of the standings once again. With P.K. Subban and Will Butcher both still on hand to compete for power-play time, Severson will also be hard-pressed to improve on his good-but-not-great production with the extra man -- he's reached double-digit power-play points in three of the last four seasons but topped out at 13.

Lee's a one-trick pony, using his 6-foot-3, 231-pound frame to carve out space in front of the net, where he's adept at deflecting pucks and burying rebounds. That skill helped him average 34 goals per season between 2016-17 and 2018-19, but his goal total dropped to just 20 in 2019-20 as the Islanders took more of a defense-first approach. A bounce-back year would require Lee to rediscover his touch on the power play, where he surprisingly scored just two goals last season after potting at least eight in each of the previous four campaigns. Given the success his team found with its physical, relatively boring style of play last season, though, the Islanders' captain will likely continue to focus on preventing chances rather than creating them.

Once heralded as one of the league's top fantasy netminders behind a powerhouse Washington team, Holtby's coming off his worst season and isn't guaranteed a starting role after signing a two-year, $8.6 million contract with Vancouver this offseason. Assuming he beats out postseason hero Thatcher Demko, Holtby will still be tasked with the challenge of bouncing back from a 2019-20 campaign which featured career worsts in GAA (3.11) and save percentage (.897). Holtby's career marks are much more respectable at 2.53 and .916, though he's now underperformed those rate stats significantly for three years running. A bounce-back campaign following his change of scenery is certainly on the table, but so is a continued decline in both performance and playing time, so buyer beware.

One of the bigger surprises in the league a season ago, Marino emerged as a legitimate top-four option for Pittsburgh before missing about three weeks of action with facial fractures suffered in February. As impressive as Marino was in his rookie season, his game isn't particularly conducive to fantasy hockey. Marino gets minimal time with the man advantage (0:45 per game) and offers minimal value in leagues that value hits (72) and blocks (77). His plus/minus should be strong, and he should pick up his fair share of even-strength points because of the talent in the Penguins lineup, but there's a very good chance Marino will be selected too high in drafts heading into the season. Don't make the mistake of reaching too far or early here.

Still just 25, Domi joined his third NHL organization following an offseason trade from Montreal to Columbus, where he immediately signed a new two-year, $10.6 million deal. Domi's production fell by the wayside in his second season with the Canadiens. After posting 28 goals and 72 points in 2018-19, Domi's numbers dropped to 17 goals and 44 points a year ago. His secondary offensive numbers (179 shots, 11 power-play points) remained steady, so there appears to be rebound potential here. The Jackets are light up front, as well, and Domi should be given every chance to outperform his current fantasy stock this season.

Pittsburgh general manager Jim Rutherford had been trying to acquire Zucker for well over a year before finally getting his man in February. Zucker responded with six goals and 12 points in 15 regular-season games with the Penguins. He played alongside Evgeni Malkin on Pittsburgh's second line during that period, along with seeing time on the second power-play unit. Zucker's role figures to be unchanged heading into 2020-21, which is a gig that should result in a decent amount of fantasy value. Keep in mind that Zucker's production would likely see a significant decrease should the oft-injured Malkin miss any time.

Silfverberg has long been labeled a sleeper pick due to the upside he flashed with 37 points in 40 playoff games from 2015-17, but he has never come close to sustaining that level over a full season, failing to crack 50 points. Given proper expectations, however, Silfverberg has proven reliable, scoring at least 39 points in each of the past six seasons while reaching the 20-goal mark four times. Another campaign in that vein is well within the 30-year-old winger's capabilities, especially since the offensively challenged Ducks lack alternatives to push Silfverberg out of a top-six role. If you're drafting Silfverberg, it's for his floor, not his ceiling.

Pettersson's a steady presence on Pittsburgh's blue line, but he hasn't shown much offensive acumen. In 126 games over the past two seasons, Pettersson has scored only four goals on 151 shots to go with a solid plus-22 rating. He has also dished 37 helpers over that span, and perhaps there's still room for Pettersson to develop some scoring touch considering he's just 24 years of age. As it stands, the solid Swede lacks scoring upside and isn't ticketed for much if any power-play time.

DeAngelo put it all together offensively in 2019-20, tying for fourth among defensemen in both goals (15) and points (53). Some regression should be expected considering his 10.1 shooting percentage from last year is likely unsustainable for a blueliner, plus Adam Fox and Jacob Trouba are both waiting in the wings should DeAngelo struggle in his role on the top power-play unit, where he racked up 19 points last year. Despite those drawbacks, there's plenty of room for the 25-year-old to take a step back and still provide excellent offensive production on a fast-paced Rangers team that scored the fifth most goals in the league last season. Plus, it's possible DeAngelo still has room to grow in other areas considering he has just two seasons of 40-plus NHL games under his belt.

Looking to create cap space to re-sign Chris Kreider, the Rangers surprisingly dealt Skjei and his $5.25 cap hit (through 2023-24) to Carolina at the deadline in exchange for a first-round pick. Skjei posted 39 points in his rookie season but has finished with either 24 or 25 points in each of the past three years. He logs plenty of heavy minutes and can help with both hits and blocks, but there simply isn't a ton here to get excited about. Skjei is probably only worth a look in the deepest of fantasy leagues.

After exploding for a career-best 35 goals and 81 points in 2018-19, Toews dipped back down to 18 goals and 60 points last season. The point total was more in line with expectations for a player who has broken 70 only twice in his 13-year career, though it was surprising to see the veteran center fall short of the 20-goal mark for the first time. Toews spends most of his even-strength minutes separated from star winger Patrick Kane, but Dominik Kubalik and Alex DeBrincat provide enough firepower for Toews to hold his own there. The real key to improving on last year's numbers will be a bounce back for Chicago's power play, which ranked fourth-worst at 15.2 percent last season. Toews scored just eight power-play points as a result after averaging more than double that over his previous 12 campaigns.
